Add range-selection support to the v0.6.2 multi-select infrastructure. Holding shift while clicking a checkbox selects all issues between the last-clicked-checkbox-on-this-surface and the current one.

### Why per-surface anchor

"Range" only makes sense within a single ordered list. The kanban shows multiple columns AND each column has its own visible order; the issues-list sidebar has its own filter-dependent order. Range across two columns is meaningless. So the anchor is per-surface — call it `anchorBySurface: Record<string, number | null>` where surface keys are e.g. `kanban:open`, `kanban:review`, `issues-list`. Clicking a checkbox without shift updates the anchor; shift-clicking selects everything between anchor and current within the same surface's visible-issue-numbers array.

### Edits to `apps/desktop/src/stores/selectionStore.ts`

Extend the existing store (added in v0.6.2 #96):

```ts
interface SelectionState {
  selectedByProject: Record<string, Set<number>>;
  /** Per-project, per-surface anchor for range selection. Reset when selection clears. */
  anchorBySurfaceByProject: Record<string, Record<string, number | null>>;
}

// New action:
rangeSelect: (surface: string, surfaceIssueNumbers: number[], targetIssueNumber: number) => void;
```

Implementation:
```ts
rangeSelect: (surface, surfaceIssueNumbers, targetIssueNumber) => set((state) => {
  const pid = getProjectId();
  const anchor = state.anchorBySurfaceByProject[pid]?.[surface];

  if (anchor === undefined || anchor === null) {
    // No anchor yet — treat shift-click as a normal toggle and set the anchor.
    const current = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
    const next = new Set(current);
    if (next.has(targetIssueNumber)) next.delete(targetIssueNumber);
    else next.add(targetIssueNumber);
    return {
      selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next },
      anchorBySurfaceByProject: {
        ...state.anchorBySurfaceByProject,
        [pid]: { ...(state.anchorBySurfaceByProject[pid] ?? {}), [surface]: targetIssueNumber },
      },
    };
  }

  // Anchor exists — compute the range in the surface's visible order.
  const anchorIdx = surfaceIssueNumbers.indexOf(anchor);
  const targetIdx = surfaceIssueNumbers.indexOf(targetIssueNumber);
  if (anchorIdx === -1 || targetIdx === -1) {
    // Anchor or target no longer visible — fall back to a plain toggle.
    const current = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
    const next = new Set(current);
    if (next.has(targetIssueNumber)) next.delete(targetIssueNumber);
    else next.add(targetIssueNumber);
    return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next } };
  }
  const [from, to] = anchorIdx < targetIdx ? [anchorIdx, targetIdx] : [targetIdx, anchorIdx];
  const current = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
  const next = new Set(current);
  for (let i = from; i <= to; i++) next.add(surfaceIssueNumbers[i]);
  return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next } };
}),
```

Update `toggle` to ALSO set the anchor (so a non-shift click sets the anchor for subsequent shift-clicks):
```ts
toggle: (n, surface?: string) => set((state) => {
  const pid = getProjectId();
  const existing = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
  const next = new Set(existing);
  if (next.has(n)) next.delete(n); else next.add(n);
  const updates: Partial<SelectionState> = {
    selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next },
  };
  if (surface) {
    updates.anchorBySurfaceByProject = {
      ...state.anchorBySurfaceByProject,
      [pid]: { ...(state.anchorBySurfaceByProject[pid] ?? {}), [surface]: n },
    };
  }
  return updates;
}),
```

Update `clear` to drop anchors too:
```ts
clear: () => set((state) => {
  const pid = getProjectId();
  return {
    selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: new Set() },
    anchorBySurfaceByProject: { ...state.anchorBySurfaceByProject, [pid]: {} },
  };
}),
```

### Surface keys

- KanbanCard: surface = `kanban:${columnId}` — passed in from KanbanColumn (it already has the column id) via a prop.
- IssueCard (sidebar): surface = `issues-list`.

### KanbanCard.tsx — wire shift detection

```tsx
const handleCheckboxClick = (e: React.MouseEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  if (e.shiftKey) {
    e.preventDefault();
    // surfaceIssueNumbers comes from a new prop (or selector) — see below.
    useSelectionStore.getState().rangeSelect(`kanban:${columnId}`, surfaceIssueNumbers, issue.number);
  }
};

<input
  type="checkbox"
  checked={isSelected}
  onChange={() => useSelectionStore.getState().toggle(issue.number, `kanban:${columnId}`)}
  onClick={handleCheckboxClick}
  onPointerDown={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}
  // ...
/>
```

The `columnId` prop is needed — pass from KanbanColumn (which already has it). Also `surfaceIssueNumbers` (the column's current visible-order array of issue numbers) — pass from KanbanColumn the same way it passes `issues`.

### IssueCard.tsx — same pattern

```tsx
onClick={(e) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  if (e.shiftKey) {
    e.preventDefault();
    useSelectionStore.getState().rangeSelect('issues-list', allVisibleIssueNumbers, issue.number);
  }
}}
onChange={() => useSelectionStore.getState().toggle(issue.number, 'issues-list')}
```

`allVisibleIssueNumbers` comes from the parent IssuesSection — pass as a prop, derived from the same filteredIssues that already feeds the list.

### Vitest tests

File: `apps/desktop/src/stores/__tests__/selectionStoreRange.test.ts`

```ts
import { describe, it, expect, beforeEach, vi } from 'vitest';

vi.mock('../projectsStore', () => ({
  useProjectsStore: { getState: () => ({ activeProjectId: 'p1' }) },
}));

import { useSelectionStore } from '../selectionStore';

beforeEach(() => {
  useSelectionStore.setState({ selectedByProject: {}, anchorBySurfaceByProject: {} });
});

describe('rangeSelect', () => {
  it('with no anchor, behaves as a plain toggle and sets the anchor', () => {
    const s = useSelectionStore.getState();
    s.rangeSelect('kanban:open', [1, 2, 3, 4], 2);
    expect(s.selected()).toEqual([2]);
    s.rangeSelect('kanban:open', [1, 2, 3, 4], 4);
    // Anchor was 2, range 2..4 selects 2, 3, 4.
    expect(s.selected()).toEqual([2, 3, 4]);
  });

  it('selects ascending range from anchor to target', () => {
    const s = useSelectionStore.getState();
    s.toggle(1, 'kanban:open');
    s.rangeSelect('kanban:open', [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], 4);
    expect(s.selected()).toEqual([1, 2, 3, 4]);
  });

  it('selects descending range (target before anchor)', () => {
    const s = useSelectionStore.getState();
    s.toggle(5, 'kanban:open');
    s.rangeSelect('kanban:open', [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], 2);
    expect(s.selected()).toEqual([2, 3, 4, 5]);
  });

  it('falls back to plain toggle when anchor no longer in surface', () => {
    const s = useSelectionStore.getState();
    s.toggle(99, 'kanban:open'); // anchor 99 not in surface list
    s.rangeSelect('kanban:open', [1, 2, 3], 2);
    expect(s.selected()).toEqual([2, 99]);
  });
});
```

### Verification

- `selectionStore.ts` adds `anchorBySurfaceByProject` state + `rangeSelect(surface, numbers, target)` action; `toggle` accepts an optional `surface` param and updates the anchor when present; `clear` resets anchors too.
- `KanbanCard.tsx` checkbox detects shiftKey on click, calls `rangeSelect` with the column's surface key + visible issue numbers.
- `IssueCard.tsx` (or the issues-list inline JSX) does the same with `surface='issues-list'`.
- 4 vitest cases pass; desktop count goes from 105 → 109.
- `pnpm build` clean.

Symmetric to v0.6.2's bulk Add Label, but the label picker shows ONLY labels currently applied to the selected issues (so the user picks from removable options).

### Edits to `apps/desktop/src/components/BulkActionToolbar.tsx`

Add a new bulk handler and a second LabelPickerPopover instance (or reuse via a `mode` prop):

```ts
const [removeLabelOpen, setRemoveLabelOpen] = useState(false);

const bulkRemoveLabel = async (labelName: string) => {
  if (busy) return;
  setBusy('label');
  setRemoveLabelOpen(false);
  const failures: number[] = [];
  await Promise.all(
    selected.map((n) =>
      invoke('edit_github_issue', { number: n, addLabels: [], removeLabels: [labelName], projectPath })
        .catch(() => { failures.push(n); })
    )
  );
  setBusy(null);
  triggerIssuesRefetch();
  if (failures.length === 0) {
    addToast(`Removed "${labelName}" from ${selected.length} issue${selected.length === 1 ? '' : 's'}.`, 'success');
  } else {
    addToast(`Removed from ${selected.length - failures.length} of ${selected.length}; failed: #${failures.join(', #')}`, 'error');
  }
};
```

Add a Remove Label button next to Add Label in the toolbar:
```tsx
<button type="button" disabled={busy !== null} onClick={() => setRemoveLabelOpen((v) => !v)}>
  {busy === 'label' ? 'Working...' : 'Remove label'}
</button>
{removeLabelOpen && (
  <LabelPickerPopover
    mode="remove"
    selectedIssueNumbers={selected}
    onPick={bulkRemoveLabel}
    onClose={() => setRemoveLabelOpen(false)}
  />
)}
```

### Edits to `apps/desktop/src/components/LabelPickerPopover.tsx`

Extend the popover to filter the displayed label list based on `mode`:

```ts
interface LabelPickerPopoverProps {
  mode?: 'add' | 'remove'; // defaults to 'add' for back-compat
  selectedIssueNumbers?: number[]; // required when mode='remove' to compute union
  onPick: (labelName: string) => void;
  onClose: () => void;
}
```

When `mode='remove'`:
1. Fetch all labels via `fetch_github_labels` (existing).
2. ALSO fetch each selected issue via `fetch_github_issue_by_number` to discover which labels are currently applied.
3. Compute the **union** of applied labels across the selection. Only those appear in the picker.
4. Show a small caption above the list: "Labels applied to selection (union)".

```ts
// Inside the existing useEffect — branch on mode:
useEffect(() => {
  setLoading(true);
  if (mode === 'remove' && selectedIssueNumbers) {
    Promise.all(
      selectedIssueNumbers.map((n) =>
        invoke<{ labels: { name: string; color: string }[] }>('fetch_github_issue_by_number', { number: n, projectPath })
      )
    )
      .then((issues) => {
        const union = new Map<string, Label>();
        issues.forEach((i) => i.labels.forEach((l) => union.set(l.name, l)));
        setLabels([...union.values()]);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch(() => { setLabels([]); setLoading(false); });
  } else {
    invoke<Label[]>('fetch_github_labels', { projectPath })
      .then((data) => { setLabels(data); setLoading(false); })
      .catch(() => { setLabels([]); setLoading(false); });
  }
}, [projectPath, mode, selectedIssueNumbers?.join(',')]);
```

The `selectedIssueNumbers?.join(',')` dep gives a stable string key — the array reference may change but its content is what matters.

When the union is empty (selected issues have no labels), show: "No labels currently applied to selection." — the user can dismiss with the Cancel button.

### Vitest tests

The label-picker logic for the union calculation is the testable bit. Extract it to a pure helper in the same file or a colocated utility:

```ts
export function unionLabels(issues: { labels: { name: string; color: string }[] }[]): Label[] {
  const union = new Map<string, Label>();
  issues.forEach((i) => i.labels.forEach((l) => union.set(l.name, l)));
  return [...union.values()];
}
```

File: `apps/desktop/src/components/__tests__/labelPickerUnion.test.ts`

```ts
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';
import { unionLabels } from '../LabelPickerPopover';

describe('unionLabels', () => {
  it('returns empty when issues have no labels', () => {
    expect(unionLabels([{ labels: [] }, { labels: [] }])).toEqual([]);
  });

  it('deduplicates labels by name across issues', () => {
    const out = unionLabels([
      { labels: [{ name: 'bug', color: 'ff0000' }, { name: 'p1', color: '00ff00' }] },
      { labels: [{ name: 'bug', color: 'ff0000' }, { name: 'p2', color: '0000ff' }] },
    ]);
    expect(out.map((l) => l.name).sort()).toEqual(['bug', 'p1', 'p2']);
  });

  it('handles a single issue with multiple labels', () => {
    const out = unionLabels([
      { labels: [{ name: 'a', color: '111111' }, { name: 'b', color: '222222' }] },
    ]);
    expect(out).toHaveLength(2);
  });
});
```

### Verification

- BulkActionToolbar gains a Remove Label button next to Add Label.
- LabelPickerPopover accepts `mode='remove'` + `selectedIssueNumbers`; fetches per-issue labels and shows the union.
- `unionLabels` helper exported and tested with 3 vitest cases (109 → 112).
- `pnpm build` clean.

Add a 'Add to release' button to the BulkActionToolbar that opens the existing ReleaseDialog in 'create' mode with the selected issues pre-populated. Reuse the existing `useReleaseDialogStore.openDialog(release?)` API.

### How the existing dialog works

`useReleaseDialogStore` has `openDialog(release?: TikiRelease)` — passing `undefined` opens for new release; passing a `TikiRelease` opens for edit. We want a third mode: "new release pre-populated with these issues". The cleanest path: pass a partial TikiRelease with `version: ''` (so it shows as 'new') and `issues: selected.map(...)`.

### Read TikiRelease shape first

Before editing, confirm the `TikiRelease` type in `apps/desktop/src/stores/tikiReleasesStore.ts` so the synthesized object matches. Likely shape:
```ts
interface TikiRelease {
  version: string;
  issues: { number: number; title: string }[];
  status?: string;
  createdAt?: string;
}
```

### Edits to BulkActionToolbar.tsx

```ts
import { useReleaseDialogStore, useIssuesStore } from '../stores';
// ...
const openReleaseDialog = useReleaseDialogStore((s) => s.openDialog);
const allIssues = useIssuesStore((s) => s.issues);

const bulkAssignToRelease = () => {
  if (busy) return;
  // Build minimal TikiRelease pre-populated with selected issue numbers + titles.
  const issues = selected
    .map((n) => {
      const found = allIssues.find((i) => i.number === n);
      return found ? { number: n, title: found.title } : { number: n, title: `#${n}` };
    });
  openReleaseDialog({
    version: '',
    issues,
  } as TikiRelease);
  // Don't clear selection — user might cancel the dialog and want to keep their selection.
};
```

Add the button to the toolbar:
```tsx
<button type="button" disabled={busy !== null} onClick={bulkAssignToRelease}>
  Add to release
</button>
```

If the existing ReleaseDialog doesn't gracefully handle the empty-version pre-populated case (e.g. it bails when `version === ''`), pass the issues some other way — possibly extend `openDialog` to accept an `{ initialIssues }` argument:

```ts
// In releaseDialogStore.ts:
interface ReleaseDialogActions {
  openDialog: (release?: TikiRelease, opts?: { initialIssues?: { number: number; title: string }[] }) => void;
  closeDialog: () => void;
}
```

Then ReleaseDialog reads `initialIssues` from the store on open and seeds its form. Choose whichever path the existing dialog accommodates with the smaller diff. Read the dialog before editing.

### Out of scope: bulk YOLO

The issue's 4th deferred item — bulk YOLO — is NOT included in this release. It needs its own UX/state design (terminal coordination, queueing, progress UI). File a NEW follow-up issue at the END of this phase, after the PR merges:

```
gh issue create --title "Bulk YOLO: enqueue selected issues into a serial /tiki:yolo cascade" --body "..."
```

Flag this in the report — the parent agent will file it.

### Vitest tests

This phase is mostly UI wiring + reuse. The testable logic is the issue-number → TikiRelease pre-population. Tiny:

```ts
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';

function buildPrePopulatedRelease(
  selected: number[],
  allIssues: { number: number; title: string }[],
) {
  return {
    version: '',
    issues: selected.map((n) => {
      const found = allIssues.find((i) => i.number === n);
      return found ? { number: n, title: found.title } : { number: n, title: `#${n}` };
    }),
  };
}

describe('buildPrePopulatedRelease', () => {
  it('matches selected issue numbers to titles when found', () => {
    const r = buildPrePopulatedRelease([2, 1], [{ number: 1, title: 'A' }, { number: 2, title: 'B' }]);
    expect(r.issues).toEqual([{ number: 2, title: 'B' }, { number: 1, title: 'A' }]);
  });

  it('falls back to # placeholder when issue not found in the list', () => {
    const r = buildPrePopulatedRelease([99], []);
    expect(r.issues).toEqual([{ number: 99, title: '#99' }]);
  });
});
```

Extract `buildPrePopulatedRelease` from BulkActionToolbar to a colocated helper file (e.g. `apps/desktop/src/components/bulkAssignHelpers.ts`) so the import is clean.

